      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! In the context of a standard discovery request, materiality refers to the legal threshold of importance, implying that the requested information must have a significant enough connection to the case's issues to warrant collection and review. Relevance, on the other hand, pertains to whether the information directly relates to or impacts a particular fact or issue in the case. Materiality is about the significance within the case, while relevance is more about the direct connection to the fact-finding process. Essentially, all material items are relevant, but not all relevant items are necessarily deemed material in the eyes of the law.",
