    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Adjusting the configuration to emphasize strict adherence to the literal interpretation of materiality is wise to ensure that time and resources are allocated to claims with a direct, significant connection to the case. By recalibrating the model to reduce the weight of subtle indicators, the evidence review process should become more streamlined, filtering out noise and focusing on material claims with a clearer, more immediate relevance.\n\n\nHowever, be mindful that this shift could also potentially omit nuanced or implicit information that might later surface as relevant. Subtle indicators can sometimes be crucial in evolving litigation landscapes, particularly in complex legal disputes where strategic implications are multifaceted. While quantitative savings are important, qualitative insights can be equally impactful.\n\n\nTo strike an optimal balance, consider implementing a tiered review process. Preliminary filtering based on stricter materiality could be followed by a secondary, casual review of the remaining documents to catch any potentially overlooked relevant subtleties. Regularly revisiting your parameters and reviewing outcomes will also ensure that your refined system continues to serve your needs accurately. This approach allows for both efficiency in the immediate workflow and maintains a safety net for those rare instances where subtle context becomes material evidence.",
